Hyper Parameter combinations

Different hyper parameters of SOM Brero model were considered with respect to FS1 and FS2 data.

Map Size:
* Larger map sizes result in more detailed patterns; smaller map sizes result in more general patterns (Delgado et al. 2017)
* With proper analysis and calculation on the number of the data rows as per (Delgado et al. 2017) gave the range from [7 and 16]

Radius Type:
* Two radius types are allowed in SOMBrero package.
* This neighborhood function used to modify the weight vectors of the neighboring units neurons. (Liu, Suleman, and N.K. Mooers 2006)
* Radius type guassian and letremy are mentioned in the SOM Brero package document by (Villa Vialaneix, n.d.)
* gaussian: Gaussian neighbourhood
* Letremy : corresponds to an piecewise linear neighbourhood

Distance Type :
* During the training process the weight vector of the winner neuraon is moved towards the presented input data by a certain fraction of the Euclidean distance
* Various distance types are allowed. All are used in the hyper parameter optimization
* letremy : is the distance of the original implementation by Patrick Letremy that switches between maximum and euclidean during the training . This distance type can only be used when radius type is letremy.

eps 0 :
* This is scaling value used for stochastic gradient descent step in the prototypes updates.
* Extreme ends were tested initially. Hence eps_0 ranges from [0.01 and 2]

Max Iteration :
* Maximum number of iterations for SOM algorithm process.
* Max value is selected as SOM brero documentation (Villa Vialaneix, n.d.)
* Hence the range is from [5.. (5*nrow(data))]

Prototype Initialization :
* Prototype for the SOM can be initialized randomly, pca or obs.
* pca: prototypes are initialized to the observations closest to a grid along the two first principal components of the data.
* obs: according to observations.

Scaling :
* Unitvar and center is used.
* Unitvar is for numeric data which is centered and scaled. Center is used when the input data is not scaled but only centered.
* Korrespe was not used as it is only applicable for the contigency tables where the frequency distribution of the variables is displayed.

Quantization Error

  • The QE is the average distance between each data vector and the BMU.(Liu, Suleman, and N.K. Mooers 2006)
  • The quantization error calculates the mean squared euclidean distance between the sample vectors and their respective cluster prototypes.
  • QE helps quantify the quality of the clustering.
  • QE declines as the map becomes larger.(Polzlbauer, n.d.)
  • Larger map sizes leads to more detailed patterns; smaller map sizes result in more general patterns.(Liu, Suleman, and N.K. Mooers 2006)
  • Quantization Error can not be used to com-pare maps of different sizes. (Polzlbauer, n.d.)

Topographic Error

  • TE is the topology preservation measure.
  • TE is calculated as the ratio of sample vectors for which the second best matching unit is not in the direct neighborhood of the best matching unit.(Liu, Suleman, and N.K. Mooers 2006)
  • For all data samples, the respective best and second-best matching units are identified.
  • If these are not adjacent on the map lattice, this is considered an error.
  • TE is always normalized in the range [0,1] . (Polzlbauer, n.d.)
  • 0 means topology is perserved perfectly (Polzlbauer, n.d.)
  • Topographic Error is not reliable for small maps.
  • TE provides an insight on the good organization on the map.

Best Mapping quality

  • Lower values of QE and TE indicate better mapping quality. (Liu, Suleman, and N.K. Mooers 2006)

  • Further analysis done on the data where TE less than 0.65 and QE less than 34 . Third quartile values considered for this.

Partial dependence

  • Need for pdp : Quantifying predictor importance.
  • Partial dependence plots are used for displying marginal dependency of predictors on the target variable.
  • Different packages can be used for analysing partial dependency such as pdp, iceplots.
  • Even some learning models like random forest and gradient booting regressor have built in method to highlight the partial dependencies.
  • PDP package visualizes the relationship between a subset of the features (max 3) and the target variable while considering the average effect of the other predictors in the model.

Analysis of impact of hyper parameters on QE and TE

  • In my thesis, PDPs will help to interpret the marginal dependency of different hyper parameters on either Quantization Error or Topographic Error ( i.e.QE or TE namely).
